# ⚙️ DocuGuard — Complete Setup Guide

Detailed installation and configuration guide for Windows, Linux, and macOS.

---

## 📋 Prerequisites

| Requirement | Minimum Version | How to Check |
|---|---|---|
| Python | 3.10+ | `python --version` |
| pip | Latest | `pip --version` |
| Git | Any | `git --version` |
| Telegram Account | — | — |

---

## 🪟 Windows

```cmd
:: Open Command Prompt or PowerShell as normal user

:: 1. Clone the repo
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/DocuGuard.git
cd DocuGuard

:: 2. Create virtual environment
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate

:: 3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

:: 4. Copy config template
copy .env.example .env

:: 5. Open config in Notepad and fill in values
notepad .env
```

---

## 🐧 Linux (Ubuntu / Kali / Parrot)

```bash
# 1. Clone the repo
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/DocuGuard.git
cd DocuGuard

# 2. Create virtual environment
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

# 3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# 4. Copy config template
cp .env.example .env

# 5. Edit config
nano .env
```

---

## 🍎 macOS

```bash
# 1. Clone the repo
git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/DocuGuard.git
cd DocuGuard

# 2. Create virtual environment
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

# 3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# 4. Copy config template
cp .env.example .env

# 5. Edit config
nano .env        # or: open -e .env
```

---

## 🤖 Creating Your Telegram Bot

### Step 1 — Open BotFather

1. Open Telegram (app or web)
2. Search: `@BotFather`
3. Look for the blue ✅ checkmark (official bot)
4. Click **START**

### Step 2 — Create the bot

Type and send:
```
/newbot
```

When asked for a **name** (display name):
```
DocuGuard
```

When asked for a **username** (must end with `bot`):
```
docuguard_yourname_bot
```
*(Replace `yourname` with your name to make it unique)*

### Step 3 — Save your token

BotFather will reply with:
```
Done! Congratulations on your new bot. 🎉

Use this token to access the HTTP API:
7123456789:AAFdef_ghIJKlmNoPQRstUvwXYZabc

Keep your token secure and store it safely,
it can be used by anyone to control your bot.
```

**Copy that token — you'll need it next.**

---

## 🔑 Configuring the .env File

Open the `.env` file you created and fill it in:

```env
# Your Telegram Bot Token from BotFather
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=7123456789:AAFdef_ghIJKlmNoPQRstUvwXYZabc

# A strong random secret key (used for HMAC signing)
SECRET_KEY=a3f9c2e1b4d8f7a0c5e2b1d9f3a8c4e7b2d5f1a6c3e9b7d4f2a8c1e5b3d7f9
```

Generate your SECRET_KEY with this command:
```bash
python -c "import secrets; print(secrets.token_hex(32))"
```

> ⚠️ **IMPORTANT:**
> - Never share your `.env` file
> - Never commit `.env` to GitHub (`.gitignore` blocks it automatically)
> - If your token leaks — go to BotFather → `/revoke` → get a new token

---

## ▶️ Running

### Option A — CLI Demo (Test crypto without Telegram)
```bash
python src/demo_cli.py
```

### Option B — Run Unit Tests
```bash
python -m pytest tests/ -v
```

### Option C — Full Telegram Bot
```bash
python src/bot.py
```

You will see:
```
🚀 DocuGuard Bot starting...
✅ Bot is running! Press Ctrl+C to stop.
```

**Do not close this terminal — the bot runs in it.**

---

## 🧪 Testing the Bot on Telegram

1. Open Telegram → search your bot username
2. Click **START** or send `/start`
3. Send any file (PDF, DOCX, TXT, image, etc.)
4. Bot will ask: **Register** or **Verify?**
5. Choose **Register** → receive your Document ID and fingerprints
6. Send the **exact same file** → choose **Verify** → see ✅ AUTHENTIC
7. Edit the file (add a space, change one word) → send again → see 🚨 TAMPERED

---

## 🛑 Stopping the Bot

Press `Ctrl + C` in the terminal where the bot is running.

---

## 🔧 Troubleshooting

| Error | Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| `No module named 'telegram'` | Package not installed | `pip install python-telegram-bot==21.5` |
| `No module named 'dotenv'` | Package not installed | `pip install python-dotenv` |
| `Unauthorized` | Wrong bot token | Re-check your `.env` file |
| `Conflict: terminated by other getUpdates` | Two bot instances running | Kill the other terminal |
| `ConnectionError` | No internet | Check network connection |
| Bot receives file but doesn't reply | Token issue or crash | Check terminal output for errors |
| `python: command not found` (Linux) | Use `python3` instead | `python3 src/bot.py` |

---

## 📁 What Each File Does

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `src/bot.py` | Main Telegram bot — handles all commands and messages |
| `src/crypto_engine.py` | Core cryptography — SHA-256, HMAC-SHA256, SHA3-256, Merkle tree |
| `src/document_store.py` | JSON registry — stores fingerprints (not file contents) |
| `src/demo_cli.py` | CLI demo — test all crypto without needing Telegram |
| `tests/test_crypto.py` | 26 automated unit tests |
| `.env.example` | Template config — copy this to `.env` |
| `.env` | Your actual config — NEVER commit this |
| `.gitignore` | Tells Git to ignore secrets, cache, etc. |
| `requirements.txt` | Python packages needed |
| `README.md` | Project overview and documentation |
| `SETUP.md` | This file |
| `SECURITY.md` | How to report security vulnerabilities |
| `LICENSE` | MIT License |
